<HEADLINE>
<P>
HEAT-SPONSORED PROGRAMS RESULT IN INCREASED AWARENESS OF SOCCER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Thomas Militello's suggestions on how to promote soccer (Times, July 26) have a 
lot of strength behind them, but I would like to point out some of the programs 
that the Los Angeles Heat have been involved in to increase awareness of the 
sport in the past year: 
</P>
<P>
* The team donated time to an anti-drug program. It did over 100 school 
assemblies promoting "Soccer is a Kick, Drugs are a Drag." 
</P>
<P>
* It offered free clinics to club and American Youth Soccer Organization teams 
in Los Angeles and Orange counties. 
</P>
<P>
* Press releases about the team are distributed to over 120 reporters, which 
has resulted in increased media coverage. 
</P>
<P>
* Ticket packages have been put together in an attempt to increase attendance 
at home games. 
</P>
<P>
This past year the team went through management changes and it wasn't until 
March when a new management team was in place. It led to a great loss of time 
in promoting the 1990 season. But our attendance has increased over 60% from 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
As for a public-address announcer, if you know of someone who loves and 
understands the game of soccer and can show enthusiasm over the microphone 
while still sounding professional, please send some references to us. 
</P>
<P>
JILL FRACISCO 
</P>
<P>
General manager, L.A. Heat 
</P>
</TEXT>
