$900,000 for administrative costs. 
</P>
<P>
"The state is satisfied with this agreement," said John Hagerty, a spokesman 
for the New Jersey Department of Environmental Protection. "Certainly it will 
go a long way toward revitalizing Jersey City." 
</P>
<P>
The state blamed the company and two other firms for the chromium contamination 
of homes and businesses in Jersey City. 
</P>
<P>
Exposure to chromium can damage lungs, livers and kidneys. 
