<HEADLINE>
<P>
PRINGLE CHALLENGER URGES DEBATES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVE LESHER, TIMES POLITICAL WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Democratic Assembly candidate Tom Umberg on Wednesday challenged his Republican 
opponent, Curt Pringle, to a series of seven one-on-one debates, declaring, "We 
owe it to the voters." 
</P>
<P>
Pringle (R-Garden Grove) said he expected to debate Umberg, but only in forums 
sponsored by independent organizations such as the League of Women Voters. 
</P>
<P>
"The time has come for Curtis and me to meet face-to-face in a series of 
debates throughout Orange County and the 72nd Assembly District," Umberg said 
in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
Umberg suggested that the candidates be free to question each other. Umberg 
campaign manager George Urch said seven debates were proposed, one every two 
weeks until the Nov. 6 election. 
</P>
<P>
Pringle said that he debated his Democratic opponent in 1988 about three times 
and that he expected a similar schedule in this race. 
</P>
<P>
"Usually, challengers like to grandstand on debates and therefore I expected 
this type of letter," Pringle said. "What he needs to know is that in this 
community they have always had debate formats and he will soon get an 
invitation from some of the established organizations. 
</P>
<P>
"I have never turned down one of those debates and I don't intend to this 
time," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
