<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO SPORTS ET CETERA: SOCKERS SIGN GOALIE NOGUEIRA FOR 1990-91 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Goalkeeper Victor Nogueira has signed with the San Diego Sockers, becoming the 
secondplayer the Sockers have signed for the 1990-91 Major Soccer League 
season. Branko Segota is in the last year of a multi-year contract. 
</P>
<P>
Nogueira, a 10-year veteran of the indoor game and in his second year with the 
Sockers, was fifth last season among MISL goalkeepers with a 3.61 average and 
an 11-13 record. In 1988-89, he was Goalkeeper of the Year and the MISL 
Championship Series MVP. 
</P>
<P>
"Victor is a good base to begin building another championship team around," 
Sockers Coach Ron Newman said. "In his two years with the Sockers, he 
established himself as one of the premier goalkeepers in the league, and I'm 
very happy to have him back in the fold." 
</P>
<P>
The Nogueira announcement brings to four the number of players who will 
definitely be back for 1990-1991. The Sockers last week matched an offer by 
Tacoma to free agent forward Rod Castro and defender Kevin Crow said at a press 
conference last week that he had agreed to a lower salary with the Sockers, 
though neither man has signed a contract yet. 
</P>
<P>
Defender Ralph Black is still talking to the Sockers, according to Newman, 
despite rumors that he is heading to Tacoma. 
</P>
<P>
BASKETBALL 
</P>
<P>
Guard Chris McKinney has signed a national letter of intent to play at San 
Diego State, according to SDSU Coach Jim Brandenburg. McKinney, 6-foot-2, 
averaged 20.9 points and seven rebounds a game in his senior year at Lincoln 
High School in East St. Louis, Ill. 
</P>
<P>
McKinney led his team to a 29-4 record and third in the state tournament, where 
he was an All-Tournament selection. He joins other Aztecs who have signed: Joe 
McNaull, Keith Balzer, Mike Ferguson and James Lewis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
