<P>
KOREA'S DAEWOO PLANS PHILIPPINE BUS FACTORY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SEOUL 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
woo Corp. and two Philippine companies have agreed to build a bus assembly 
plant in the Philippines. 
</P>
<P>
Daewoo will have a 40% stake in the operation, First Philippine Holding Corp. 
will have 40%, and Westmont Asia Motors Corp. will hold 20%. Total investment 
will be $10 million. 
</P>
<P>
Construction will begin in October on the outskirts of Manila. The plant, which 
will be completed in a year, will have a capacity of 600 buses a year, Daewoo 
said. 
</P>
<P>
The factory will assemble buses from kits manufactured in Korea by Daewoo Motor 
Co. Daewoo Motor is a 50-50 joint venture with General Motors Corp. 
</P>
