<HEADLINE>
<P>
LIZ SMITH: ITALY WOWED BY PRINCE'S SECURITY, NOT HIS SHOW 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LIZ SMITH 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADONNA, THAT ambitious blonde, isn't the only rock star touring Europe who 
didn't bowl over Italy. Prince, who is hoping to wow the world with his new 
"Graffiti Bridge" album and film, did not exactly set Rome on fire, either. 
There were plenty of empty seats at his concert, but that's not what had the 
cognoscenti buzzing. 
</P>
<P>
No, what really amused the Italians was that Prince was surrounded by more 
security than anyone in Italy has ever seen. The hotel where Prince reigned was 
literally an armed camp of security men and bodyguards. What they were 
protecting Prince from was something of a mystery since there was not a single 
fan waiting for him outside the hotel. 
</P>
<P>
So what is it with all these bodyguards? Are stars really so afraid of being 
molested by their fans -- or those who are not their fans -- or is this simply 
part of the show, a necessary adjunct of being a superstar? 
</P>
<P>
Madonna's muscular security guys, who double as her jogging partners, were not 
favorites of the British recently, as they shoved reporters and photographers 
aside to make a path for the fanatically athletic star. 
</P>
<P>
But it is Eddie Murphy who most likely gets top honors in the bodyguard 
sweepstakes. At the opening of Spike Lee's "Mo' Better Blues" the other night, 
Murphy, whose appeal to moviegoers seems a bit on the wane, appeared with five 
times the security the mayor of New York had. 
</P>
<P>
TINA TURNER'S "Foreign Affair" concert tour of Europe has been extended for 10 
more weeks. Tina, who has more energy, stamina and sex appeal than women half 
her age, has been absolutely killing them on the Continent. She has probably 
played to the largest crowds, in the biggest arenas, in more cities than any 
other female performer. 
</P>
<P>
Just before Tina went on before 65,000 screaming fans at Woburn Abbey outside 
London last week, she was visited backstage by one very special fan -- a 
charmingly dressed down Princess Diana. Afterward, the Princess of Wales and 
her party stayed for the entire two-hour performance, watching from the 
lighting platform in the middle -- and above -- the crowd. 
</P>
<P>
BARBRA STREISAND is a woman who knows what she likes, and she wants what she 
likes right away. Just ask the delighted proprietors of the Rhett Gallery in 
Beaufort, S.C., where La Streisand is in the midst of her "Prince of Tides" 
film. 
</P>
<P>
The star, who has a fine eye for art, intended only a brief drop-in at the 
gallery. It turned into a two-hour visit. Barbra purchased at least 14 works 
that will eventually find their way to the actress's East and West Coast 
residences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Prince 
</P>
